<subSubSection pageId="54" pageNumber="55" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="54.[151,1437,1368,2043]" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">Morphology. D VI + I,14; A I,12–13; P 20–21. Large goby with stout body, moderately long snout with moderately steep profile, thick lips. Caudal peduncle deep, but lower than body depth. First dorsal fin higher than the second dorsal fin; first dorsal fin spines decreasing posteriorly, shaping a curved margin. Caudal fin rounded. Predorsal area and nape scaled. Scales small, visible on body and predorsal area as dense pattern.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="54.[151,1437,1368,2043]" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">
Live coloration. Body mostly mottled brown, with 
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">large darker, squarish midlateral blotches, each one preceded and followed by a white patch</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[661,748,1584,1611]" captionStart="FIGURE 15" captionStartId="21.[151,250,1058,1082]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1034]" captionTargetId="figure-18@21.[151,1436,181,1034]" captionTargetPageId="21" captionText="FIGURE 15. Live coloration in its natural habitat of Gobius cruentatus. Photo by S. Guerrieri, Tuscany, Italy." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6601611" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6601611/files/figure.png" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">Fig. 15</figureCitation>
). Back with 4 broad dark transverse bands, the second and fourth the darkest, separated by 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[508,722,1620,1646]" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">thin white saddles</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[737,820,1620,1647]" captionStart="FIGURE 15" captionStartId="21.[151,250,1058,1082]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1034]" captionTargetId="figure-18@21.[151,1436,181,1034]" captionTargetPageId="21" captionText="FIGURE 15. Live coloration in its natural habitat of Gobius cruentatus. Photo by S. Guerrieri, Tuscany, Italy." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6601611" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6601611/files/figure.png" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">Fig. 15</figureCitation>
). 
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">Lips mostly vermilion, with a white bar below eye, at angle of mouth</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[379,461,1656,1683]" captionStart="FIGURE 15" captionStartId="21.[151,250,1058,1082]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1034]" captionTargetId="figure-18@21.[151,1436,181,1034]" captionTargetPageId="21" captionText="FIGURE 15. Live coloration in its natural habitat of Gobius cruentatus. Photo by S. Guerrieri, Tuscany, Italy." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6601611" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6601611/files/figure.png" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">Fig. 15</figureCitation>
) (red color usually not detectable under natural light only). Membranes of both dorsal fins are highly variegated, mixing irregular patches of red, dark brown and white coloration. Rows of head sensory papillae well-visible and bicolored black and white.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="54.[151,1437,1368,2043]" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">
Similar species. No similar species in the Mediterranean. However, with no artificial light, may be confused with 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Linnaeus" authorityYear="1758" box="[208,419,1800,1826]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Gobiidae" genus="Gobius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="54" pageNumber="55" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="paganellus">
<emphasis box="[208,419,1800,1826]" italics="true" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">Gobius paganellus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
or 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Linnaeus" authorityYear="1758" box="[456,549,1800,1826]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Gobiidae" genus="Gobius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="54" pageNumber="55" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="niger">
<emphasis box="[456,549,1800,1826]" italics="true" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">G. niger</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="54.[151,1437,1368,2043]" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">
Habitat. Infralittoral species, known from 
<quantity box="[660,743,1836,1863]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.05" metricValueMax="4.0" metricValueMin="0.1" pageId="54" pageNumber="55" unit="m" value="20.5" valueMax="40.0" valueMin="1.0">1–40 m</quantity>
depth on inshore rocky habitats, sand with stones and boulders, and in seagrass meadows (Miller 1986; 
<bibRefCitation author="Louisy, P." box="[598,741,1872,1899]" pageId="54" pageNumber="55" refId="ref60639" refString="Louisy, P. (2015) Europe and Mediterranean Marine Fish Identification Guide. 3 rd Edition. Eugen Ulmer Ed., Paris, 512 pp." type="book" year="2015">Louisy 2015</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Patzner, R. A." box="[753,904,1872,1899]" pageId="54" pageNumber="55" refId="ref62855" refString="Patzner, R. A. (2021) Gobiidae. Available from: http: // www. patzner. sbg. ac. at / Gobiidae / GobiidaeSpecies. htm (accessed 1 October 2021)" type="url" year="2021">Patzner 2021</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="54.[151,1437,1368,2043]" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">
Geographic distribution. Northeastern Atlantic, Mediterranean and Black Sea (
<bibRefCitation author="Engin, S. &amp; Turan, D. &amp; Kovacic, M." box="[1108,1317,1908,1935]" pageId="54" pageNumber="55" pagination="87 - 88" refId="ref53866" refString="Engin, S., Turan, D. &amp; Kovacic, M. (2007) First record of the red-mouthed goby, Gobius cruentatus (Gobiidae), in the Black Sea. Cybium, 31, 87 - 88. https: // doi. org / 10.26028 / cybium / 2007 - 311 - 012" type="journal article" year="2007">
Engin 
<emphasis box="[1188,1241,1908,1934]" italics="true" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">et al</emphasis>
. 2007
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Vasil'eva, E. D." pageId="54" pageNumber="55" refId="ref65796" refString="Vasil'eva, E. D. (2007) Fish of the Black Sea. Key to marine, brackish-water, euryhaline, and anadromous species with color illustrations, collected by S. V. Bogorodsky. VNIRO Publishing, Moscow, 237 pp. [in Russian, with English abstract]" type="book" year="2007">Vasil’eva 2007</bibRefCitation>
). In the Atlantic, occurs from the counties of Cork and Kerry in Ireland to 
<collectingCountry box="[1030,1203,1944,1971]" name="Western Sahara" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">Western Sahara</collectingCountry>
(Miller 1986). In the Mediterranean, all along the northern coast, and along the southern coast in 
<collectingCountry box="[1012,1116,1981,2007]" name="Morocco" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">Morocco</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[1126,1210,1980,2006]" name="Algeria" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">Algeria</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[1266,1349,1980,2006]" name="Tunisia" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">Tunisia</collectingCountry>
(Miller 1986), as well as in 
<collectingRegion box="[375,481,2016,2042]" country="Libya" name="Banghazi" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">Benghazi</collectingRegion>
in 
<collectingCountry box="[517,582,2016,2042]" name="Libya" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">Libya</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Al-Hassan, L. A. J. &amp; El-Silini, O." box="[597,914,2016,2042]" pageId="54" pageNumber="55" pagination="291 - 301" refId="ref50837" refString="Al-Hassan, L. A. J. &amp; El-Silini, O. A (1999) Check-list of bony fishes collected from the Mediterranean coast of Benghazi, Libya. Revista de Biologia Marina y Oceanografia, 34, 291 - 301." type="journal article" year="1999">Al-Hassan &amp; El-Silini 1999</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
